Chapter 2 - Time series graphics

2.1 \(ts\) objects

\(ts\) function turn data to time series

y <- ts(c(123,39,78,52,110),start = 2012)

Suppose we have vector z, we can write

z <- runif(24,1,100)
y <- ts(z, start = 2003, frequency = 12)

2.3 Times series patterns

Trend - long term increase or decrease
Seasonal - pattern occurs when data is affected by seasonal factors. Usually, fix and known frequency.
Cyclic - pattern occurs not in fix frequency and usually at least 2 years.

2.4 Seasonal plots

To identify seasonality

Examples

Seasonal plot

ggseasonplot(a10, year.labels=TRUE, year.labels.left=TRUE) +
  ylab("$ million") +
  ggtitle("Seasonal plot: antidiabetic drug sales")

Polar plot

ggseasonplot(a10, polar=TRUE) +
  ylab("$ million") +
  ggtitle("Polar seasonal plot: antidiabetic drug sales")

Seasonal subseries plot

ggsubseriesplot(a10) +
  ylab("$ million") +
  ggtitle("Seasonal subseries plot: antidiabetic drug sales")

2.6 Scatter plot

Use to explore relationship between time series.

Examples

Data to time

autoplot(elecdemand[,c("Demand","Temperature")], facets=TRUE) +
  xlab("Year: 2014") + ylab("") +
  ggtitle("Half-hourly electricity demand: Victoria, Australia")

Variable to variable

qplot(Temperature, Demand, data=as.data.frame(elecdemand)) +
  ylab("Demand (GW)") + xlab("Temperature (Celsius)")

Correlation Linear relationship between variables.

\(r = \frac{\sum(x_t-\bar{x})(y_t-\bar{y})}{\sqrt{\sum(x_t-\bar{x})^2}{\sqrt{\sum(y_t-\bar{y})^2}}}\)

2.7 Lag plots

beer2 <- window(ausbeer, start=1992)
gglagplot(beer2)

2.8 Autocorrelation

Correlation of the time series data with its lagged values. \(T\) is the lenght of the time series.

\(r_k = \frac{\sum_{t=k+1}^T(y_t-\bar{y})(y_{t-k}-\bar{y})}{\sum_{t=1}^T(y_t-\bar{y})^2}\)

Example

ggAcf(beer2)

In an ACF, trended time series tend to have positive values that slowly decrease as the lag increase. When itâ€™s seasonal, ACF is larger on the seaonal lags. If both, there is a combination of pattern from trend and season.

aelec <- window(elec, start=1980)
autoplot(aelec) + xlab("Year") + ylab("GWh")

ggAcf(aelec, lag=48)

2.9 White noise

If the time series show no autocorrelation. Not necessarily equal to zero, we expect at least 95% of the spikes in ACF plot to lie within \(\pm2/\sqrt{T}\).

Example

set.seed(30)
y <- ts(rnorm(50))
autoplot(y) + ggtitle("White noise")

ggAcf(y)
